## `End`


### Signature

<pre>interface End </pre>




An End event represents the "end" of a <a href="source.md#source">Source</a>, and has no additional properties. After a Sink receives an End event, it will be disposed and will not take any more events.

### Example

```ts
function onEvent(event: Event<unknown>): void {
    console.log(event.type);
};
const sink = Sink(onEvent);
sink(End); // This disposes the sink, then calls `onEvent` above.
// Logs:
// `${EndType}`
```

### Signature

<pre>var End: <a href="#end">End</a></pre>

## `Event`

This is the base construct for distributing values/messages. All things pushed and received to and from <a href="sink.md#sink">Sinks</a> will be events. An event is an object which consists of a `type` field, which determines the type of the event. There are three types of events: <a href="#push">Push</a>, <a href="#throw">Throw</a> and <a href="#end">End</a> events:

- A Push event represents the "pushing" of a value to a sink, and has a `value` field equal to the value the event is carrying.

- A Throw represents the "throwing" of an error, and has an `error` field equal to the error the event is carrying. After a Sink receives an Error event, it will be disposed and will not take any more events.

- An End event represents the "end" of a source, and has no additional properties. After a Sink receives an End event, it will be disposed and will not take any more events.

When determining an event's type, you should \*\*always\*\* use either <a href="#pushtype">PushType</a>, <a href="#throwtype">ThrowType</a> or <a href="#endtype">EndType</a> directly instead of their constant number values.

### Example

```ts
const sink = Sink<number>(event => {
    console.log(event.type); // Either `PushType`, `ThrowType` or `EndType`.
    if (event.type === PushType) {
        // In this case event.value this will be of type `number`.
        console.log('value:', event.value);
    } else if (event.type === ThrowType) {
        const error = event.error; // This is of type `unknown`.
        console.log('error', event.error);
    }
});
sink(Push(2)); // `${PushType}`, value: 2.
sink(Throw(new Error('...'))); // `${ThrowType}`, Error(...).
```

### Signature

<pre>type Event&lt;T&gt; = <a href="#push">Push</a>&lt;T&gt; \| <a href="#throw">Throw</a> \| <a href="#end">End</a>;</pre>

## `Push`

A Push event represents the "pushing" of a value to a <a href="sink.md#sink">Sink</a>, and has a `value` field equal to the value the event is carrying.

### Example

```ts
const event = Push([1, 2, 3]);
console.log(event.type); // `${PushType}`.
console.log(event.value); // [1, 2, 3].
```

### Signature

<pre>function Push&lt;T&gt;(): <a href="#push">Push</a>&lt;undefined&gt;;</pre>

## `Throw`

A Throw represents the "throwing" of an error, and has an `error` field equal to the error the event is carrying. After a <a href="sink.md#sink">Sink</a> receives an Error event, it will be disposed and will not take any more events.

### Example

```ts
const event = Throw(new Error(...));
console.log(event.type); // `${ThrowType}`.
console.log(event.value); // Error(...).
```

### Signature

<pre>function Throw(error: unknown): <a href="#throw">Throw</a>;</pre>
